# Cloudflare Pages routing. Rules are evaluated top-to-bottom, first match wins,
# and real static assets (index.html, sandbox.html, privacy.html, /assets/*, …)
# are served before any 200 rewrite below applies.
#
# NOTE: do NOT add a top-level /404.html file. Cloudflare Pages only runs its
# SPA fallback (this file's `/* /index.html 200`) when there is NO top-level
# 404.html — when one exists, Pages serves it for every not-found path and the
# rewrite below never fires, 404'ing all deep links (/create, /play) on refresh.
# Unknown routes are handled in-app by react-router's catch-all instead.
# Also: 404 is not a valid _redirects status (only 200 / 301-308); never use it.
#
# Asset guard — critical: a request for a MISSING build asset must NOT fall back
# to index.html. The SPA fallback serves index.html as 200 text/html, so a miss
# during a deploy-propagation window can get cached at the edge; every later
# request for that hashed chunk then returns HTML and the browser fails the module
# import with "Expected a JavaScript module but got text/html". Existing assets
# are served as files before this rule ever runs; only a MISSING /assets/* reaches
# it, where proxy-to-self resolves to no file → Cloudflare's automatic 404,
# keeping the response uncacheable-as-asset instead of HTML. Must precede /*.
/assets/* /assets/:splat 200
#
# SPA fallback for the client-side router (react-router). Routes like /play and
# /create have no backing file, so direct loads / refreshes resolve to index.html
# and the router takes over. Listed after the asset guard so it never shadows it.
/* /index.html 200
